Working directories

You can set the working directory of your document using the setwd() function. You can check the current working directory using getwd(). Alternatively, you can set the working directory manually in RStudio (Session > Set Working Directory).

Install packages

Packages can be installed from RStudio using the Packages tab (normally in the bottom right window). Search for the package you want and hit enter. You can manually install packages from the console using the install.packages() function. Ex. install.packages('devtools').

Loading packages

To load a package after you have installed it, use the library() function.

library(lingStuff)

Comments

In R, anything that comes after # is considered a comment. Comments are important because they help you to remember what you did, why you did it, etc.

#############################
# Always comment your code! #
#############################

# This is a comment
2 + 2
## [1] 4

R as a calculator

This isnt incredibly useful, but it gives you an idea of how R works.

#####################
# R as a calculator #
#####################

2 + 2
## [1] 4
4^2
## [1] 16
(12 * 15) / 2
## [1] 90

Assigning variables

##################
# R uses objects #
##################

# Store the value '2' to the object 'x'
x <- 2
print(x)
## [1] 2
# Perform an operation on 'x'
x + 4
## [1] 6

Data structures

###################
# Data structures #
###################

# Vectors #

# We will create 3 vectos: x, y, and z
x <- c(1, 2, 3)
y <- c(4, 5, 6)
z <- c('a', 'b', 'c')

# We can use the print function to see the vectors in the console
print(x); print(y); print(z)
## [1] 1 2 3
## [1] 4 5 6
## [1] "a" "b" "c"
# We can perform operations on vectors
# add one to each value in the vector
# (this is much more important that it seems!)
x + 1 
## [1] 2 3 4
# add the values in x to the values in y 
x + y 
## [1] 5 7 9
# add the values of y to the values of z (this gives an error)
# Why? What type of vector is 'x'? and 'y'?
y + z
# Matrices #
# Matrices = 2d vectors

matrix(1:10, nrow = 5, ncol = 2)
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]    1    6
## [2,]    2    7
## [3,]    3    8
## [4,]    4    9
## [5,]    5   10
# Dataframes #
# Dataframes = 2d matrices with column and row names
# IMPORTANT: a column in a dataframe is like a vector, 
# each column can be of a different type (factor, numeric, etc.)

# createa a dataframe using the vectors 'x', 'y', and 'z'
testDF <- data.frame(x, y, z)
print(testDF)
##   x y z
## 1 1 4 a
## 2 2 5 b
## 3 3 6 c
# Let's look at some more interesting dataframes
# The head() function shows the 1st six rows of a dataframe
head(mtcars)

Generate a report

Using Rmarkdown

  • Open a template .Rmd file (File > New File > RMarkdown)
  • knit

Using an R script

  • .R files can be spun into .html files using the spin function
    Ex.
    knitr::spin('myscript.R')

Make sure to set the working directory
